Period Description: The latter part of the fifteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the tenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the fifteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

A Mid Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval, preceded by the Anglian and followed by the Wolstonian.
The early part of the thirteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The third century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
The latter part of the fourteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
Dating to the reign of Elizabeth I of England.
Begins with the dissolution of the monasteries and ends with the death of Queen Victoria. Use more specific period where known.
A Mid Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval, preceded by the Cromerian and followed by the Hoxnian.
The early part of the tenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The Roman period traditionally begins with the Roman invasion in 43AD and ends with the emperor Honorius directing Britain to see to its own defence in 410AD.
The early part of the third century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The Middle Stone Age, falling between the Palaeolithic and the Neolithic; marks the beginning of a move from a hunter gatherer society towards food producing society.
The latter part of the eighth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the fourteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The New Stone Age, this period follows on from the Palaeolithic and the Mesolithic and is itself succeeded by the Bronze Age. This period is characterized by the practice of a farming economy and extensive monumental constructions.
The early part of the twentieth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
A Mid Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval, preceded by the Hoxnian and followed by the Ipswichian.

A specific subdivision of the Early Medieval period encompassing the era during which there was a settled Scandinavian presence and cultural influence in England, from the invasion of the 'Great Heathen Army' in 865 AD to the defeat of Harold Hardrada at Stamford Bridge in 1066 AD. Use only to refer to Heritage Assets or resources that have an explicitly Scandinavian character or origin.
This period follows on from the Neolithic and is characterized by the increasing use of Bronzework. It is subdivided in the Early, Middle and Late Bronze Age.
The latter part of the sixteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second of three subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch.

The second subdivision of the Early Medieval period. The use of the term Anglo-Saxon is generally no longer favoured when refering to the historical period, but no satisfactory alternative for this subdivision has been identified. The period approximately encompasses the period of the Mercian supremacy, the 'golden age' of monastic learning exemplified by Bede, the Viking raids and establishment of the Danelaw and the reaction against these incursions led by King Alfred of Wessex.
The sixth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The period covering the reign of Edward VII. Do not use for the reigns of Edwards I-VI.
The last Late Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval, preceded by the Ipswichian.

Romano-British culture is the name given to the social and material culture resulting from the adoption, adaptation and reinterpretation of Roman artistic, cultural, economic and social practices by the indigenous British population, beginning with the Roman conquest of 43 AD but potentially continuing in some areas of southern Britain well into the mid-late 5th Century, after Rome had withdrawn from the province.
For monuments that can be identified only to a date range from Palaeolithic to Iron Age.

A period of civil wars in England fought between Royalists (supporters of King Charles I, also known as Cavaliers) and Parliamentarians (led first by Thomas Fairfax and later by Oliver Cromwell, also known as Roundheads) over the manner of England's governance and religious freedoms. King Charles I was executed in 1649 and the Commonwealth established, but the Civil War did not truly conclude until the defeat of Charles II's forces at the Battle of Worcester in 1651, and his subsequent escape to France.
The latter part of the eighteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the sixteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second subdivision of the Palaeolithic or Old Stone Age. Characterized by the fine flake tools of the Mousterian tradition and economically by a hunter gatherer society.
The early part of the eighteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

This is only to be used in reference to material culture, architecture and literature of 'Anglo-Saxon' stylistic character, as opposed to the broader historical period, which is to be recorded under Early Medieval or its sub-periods.
The middle part of the ninth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
Dating to the reign of the Stuart kings of England (including the Commonwealth inter-regnum)

An Early-to-Mid Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval, preceded by the Beestonian and followed by the Anglian.

The period once referred to as the Old Stone Age. It is defined by the practice of hunting and gathering and the use of chipped flint tools. This period is usually divided up into the Lower, Middle and Upper Palaeolithic.

Period named for the restoration of the English monarchy under Charles II, after the collapse of the republican Commonwealth. While the term 'Restoration' has been used to cover only the reigns of Charles II and his brother James II, it is also commonly used in reference to the remainder of the Stuart dynasty, from the reinstatement of Charles II through to the death of Queen Anne. It is also used to refer to art and literature of the era.
The last of the three periods of the Cenozoic Era. It is the period in which we live.
The early part of the first century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second of the two epochs of the Quaternary Period. It is the epoch in which we live.
The latter part of the sixth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The fourteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The twenty-first century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

Used to record buildings, defensive monuments and sites dating to, and associated with, the Second World War. For other types of building, such as houses, built during this period use MID 20TH CENTURY.
The Medieval period or Middle Ages begins with the Norman invasion and ends with the dissolution of the monasteries.
The early part of the fourteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The fifth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

A Late Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval, preceded by the Wolstonian and followed by the Devensian.
Dating to the reign of James I of England (VI of Scotland).
The first subdivision of the Medieval period, from the Norman Conquest through to the death of the King John, the last ruler of the Angevin dynasty.
The middle part of the fourth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The first century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the seventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the second century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The ninth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the seventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The seventeenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The eleventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The first subdivision of the Early Medieval period, approximately encompasing the period from the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain to the establishment of seven distinct kingdoms in what is now England, and the Christianisation of the kingdoms of Kent and Northumberland.
The early part of the ninth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
For monuments that can be identified only to a date range from Neolithic to Iron Age.
The seventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
Dating to the reign of Queen Victoria.
The middle part of the third century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

A period of civil war in England, fought as a result of a succession crisis following the death of Henry I without a living, legitimate male heir. The war was fought between supporters of Henry's daughter (and named heir) Empress Matilda and his nephew Stephen of Blois. Use only to record buildings, defensive heritage assets and other resources associated with this conflict. For other assets dating to this period, use High Medieval.
The earliest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.

The earliest subdivision of the Palaeolithic, or Old Stone Age; when the earliest use of flint tools appears in the current archaeological record. A hunter gatherer society is a defining characteristic.
The latter part of the second century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The third and final subdivision of the Early Medieval period, approximately encompassing the gradual formation of a unified kingdom of England, the Danish conquests by Swein Forkbeard and Cnut, and ending with the Norman Conquest of 1066.
The middle part of the seventeenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The earliest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
The fourth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The fifteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The earliest subdivision of the Iron Age.
The nineteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the third century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second subdivision of the Bronze Age.
The latter part of the fourth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the fifth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the eleventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the twentieth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The period during which England and Wales, and later Scotland and Ireland, were governed as a republic known as the Commonwealth. From 1649-1653 the Commonwealth was governed by a Council of State and successive Parliaments. From 1653 Oliver Cromwell was made head of state, with the title of Lord Protector. Cromwell died and was succeeded by his son Richard in 1658, but he was unable to maintain political stability and lost power in 1659. In 1660 King Charles II was restored to the throne and the monarchy reestablished.
The latter part of the nineteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the eighteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the eleventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The early part of the nineteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the ninth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
Dating to the reign of the Tudor monarchs.

The period of political and military opposition between the major Superpowers (USA and USSR) and their allies. Known as the Cold War as there were no direct military conflicts between the two main protagonists. Use to record buildings, defensive monuments and sites dating to, and associated with, the Cold War - otherwise, use Mid or Late 20th Century.
Dating to the reign of Charles I of England.
The latter part of the first century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

Relating to the period between the First World War and Second World War in Britain, and in particular the rapid expansion of housing and the development of suburbs. To be used only in reference to Heritage Assets or other resources which are explicitly described as being characteristic of the Interwar period, particularly with regard to housing and suburban expansion. Otherwise, use Early 20th Century or Mid 20th Century.
The earliest subdivision of the Bronze Age.
The second century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The twelfth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the fifteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the sixth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The early part of the fifth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

While the Regency period technically only refers to the years 1811-1820, during which Prince George (later George IV) ruled as Prince Regent due to his father George III's declining health, the term is used more broadly in architecture, art and fashion to refer to the period from the latter part of George III's reign to the end of the Georgian/Hanoverian period. Use only for Heritage Assets or resources that are specifically referred to as being 'Regency' in character - for the broader time period, use Georgian.
The middle part of the eleventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the fifth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
For monuments which are characteristic of the Palaeolithic to Mesolithic but cannot be specifically assigned.
The early part of the eighth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.
The middle part of the twelfth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The second subdivision of the Medieval period, from the accession of Henry III and the start of the Plantagenet dynasty to the death of Richard III at the Battle of Bosworth Field and the beginning of the Tudor dynasty under Henry VII.
The tenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the thirteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The first of three subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch.
The third and latest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
The latter part of the seventh century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The eighteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
This period follows on from the Bronze Age and is characterized by the use of iron for making tools and monuments such as hillforts and oppida. The Iron Age is taken to end with the Roman invasion.
The third and latest subdivision of the Bronze Age.

Dating to or characteristic of the reigns of any of the first four kings of Great Britain called George. The period is often extended to include the short reign of William IV (1830-1837), although this extended definition can also be referred to as 'Hanoverian'.
The eighth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
Catch all for uncertain period allocations
The early part of the twelfth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The last of three subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch.
The early part of the seventeenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

The period encompassing the military campaigns which together comprised the Roman Conquest of Britain, beginning in 43 AD under the Emperor Claudius with the invasion led by Aulus Plautius against the Catuvellauni, and ending with the formal establishment of Britannia's northern border along the Stanegate road between Corbridge and Carlisle in 87 AD. Use only for Heritage Assets directly related to this military campaign.
The third and last subdivision of the Palaeolithic or Old Stone Age; characterized by the development of projectile points made from bony materials and the development of fine blade flint tools.
The twentieth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar. Previously recorded as 'Modern'.
The middle part of the sixth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

Used to record buildings, defensive monuments and sites dating to, and associated with, the First World War. For other types of building, such as houses, built during this period use EARLY 20TH CENTURY.
The early part of the fourth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
An Early Pleistocene stage in the British onshore Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval, followed by the Cromerian.
The thirteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the thirteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.

Relating to the revolt against Roman rule led by Boudica of the Iceni tribe, which led to the razing of Camulodunum (Colchester), Londinium (London) and Verulamium (St Albans) before the Romans, led by Gaius Suetonius Paulinus, defeated Boudica's forces in battle at an unknown location along the course of Watling Street.
The middle part of the sixteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the tenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The third and latest subdivision of the Iron Age.
The sixteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the first century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The first of the two epochs of the Quaternary Period.
The latter part of the seventeenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
This dates from the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain to the Norman invasion in 1066 and is to be used broadly for monuments of post Roman, Saxon and Viking date. Use more specific term where known.
The middle part of the second century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The second subdivision of the Iron Age.
The middle part of the nineteenth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The middle part of the eighth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
The latter part of the twentieth century of the current calendar era (Anno Domini or Common Era) according to the Gregorian Calendar.
